Overview

This lab demonstrates how LLMNR (Link-Local Multicast Name Resolution) can be abused in an internal Active Directory environment to capture NTLMv2 authentication hashes when DNS resolution fails.

When a Windows host cannot resolve a name through DNS, it may fall back to LLMNR or NBT-NS. If an attacker answers that request first, the victim may attempt to authenticate to the attacker-controlled host, exposing an NTLM challenge-response hash that can later be cracked offline or used in follow-on attack paths.

Objective
Identify where LLMNR/NBT-NS fallback occurs
Poison name resolution requests with Responder
Capture NTLMv2 hashes
Prepare captured material for password cracking or relay follow-up
Demonstrate why LLMNR is a serious internal network weakness
